{
  "id": "U2L12",
  "title": "U2 Vocabulary list",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Koine Greek first declension nouns can be grouped according to their nominative singular endings and stem behavior. Below are common examples grouped by -η (eta), -α (alpha), and hybrid (sibilant stem) nouns."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Eta-stem nouns (ending in -η):"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "1. φωνή — voice, sound"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "2. ἀρχή — beginning, authority"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "3. ζωή — life"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "4. γραφή — writing, Scripture"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Alpha-stem nouns (ending in -α):"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "5. χώρα — land, region"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "6. ἀλήθεια — truth"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "7. νεανίας — young man"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Hybrid (sibilant stem) nouns (stems ending in ξ, σ, or ζ):"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "8. δόξα — glory (ξ-stem)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "9. θάλασσα — sea (σ-stem)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "10. γλῶσσα — tongue, language (σ-stem)"
    }
  ]
}
